article.description: Ray Allen is back and the Seattle SuperSonics think they're going to be a different team with him.
article.headline: Allen notched 24 points in 23 minutes
article.linkText: Allen sinks 24 points in Sonics' win over Suns
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Ray Allen is back and the Seattle SuperSonics think they're going to be a different team with him. Allen rejoined the Sonics after missing the first 25 games and scored 24 points in a 116-90 victory over the Phoenix Suns on Tuesday night. The three-time All-Star shooting guard, sidelined with an ankle injury, started for the Sonics but was limited to 23 minutes. He made 8 of 13 shots and had seven assists. Rashard Lewis added 22 points and tied his season high with 13 rebounds, while Ronald Murray had 17 points in reserve for Seattle. "Without him, we were a pretty good team, an average team. We probably would have finished up .500," center Jerome James said. "With him, we're a playoff team. I'm confident we can make it now." Joe Johnson scored 21 points, Shawn Marion 19 and Stephon Marbury 17 for the Suns, who dropped to 2-9 without forward Amare Stoudemire, who sprained his left ankle at Boston on Dec. 5. Stoudemire is out until mid-January. Allen underwent surgery on his right ankle Nov. 1 for removal of a bone chip that bothered him during training camp. It was the first operation of his career. Allen averaged 24.5 points in 29 games for the Sonics last season after being acquired in a trade with Milwaukee that sent Gary Payton to the Bucks. "I downplayed my return a lot because I didn't expect to be in great shape," Allen said. "But from all the rehab I've been doing, when I stepped on the floor I felt at home." The former Connecticut star who was the fifth pick in the 1996 draft said he was surprised he was so productive. "I tried to hide me being tired out there on the floor as much as I could," Allen said. "But we've got a lot of great players on this team so it made it a lot easier on me." Sonics coach Nate McMillan was almost euphoric after the game. "A lot of times when guys are off a long period of time, in that first game they're very nervous," McMillan said. "But Ray Allen looked like he didn't miss a beat. He came out sharp. He looked better tonight than he did in practice those two days." The Sonics broke open a close game in the third quarter. Lewis hit a 17-footer and a 3-pointer to start a 12-2 run by Seattle, with Vladimir Radmanovic capping it with another 3-pointer for a 75-60 lead for the Sonics with 6:33 left in the period. The Sonics led 88-68 at the end of the third quarter. Marbury made a 32-foot jumper at the buzzer to cut Seattle's lead to 53-48 at halftime after rookie Luke Ridnour made a jump shot for Seattle with 3.6 seconds to go as time ran out on the shot clock. Marbury said the Suns have to pick up the pace if they're going to survive without the 6-foot-10, 245-pound Stoudemire. "We aren't playing aggressive on the defensive end," he said. "Right now is not the time for that to be happening. As a team, we can't afford that." Mike D'Antoni, Phoenix's coach who replaced the fired Frank Johnson on Dec. 10, didn't like what he saw. "It was a disappointing loss," said D'Antoni, whose Suns are 2-6 under him. "Not the loss, but the effort. That's something that we need to take a real good look at and understand why." Forward Donnell Harvey, acquired in a trade Tuesday from Orlando, made his debut for the Suns in the second quarter. He had a flagrant foul called on him against Antonio Daniels in the fourth quarter. Harvey played 14 minutes and got two rebounds and two points.

Game notes
The SuperSonics were 12-13 without Allen. ... With the national security level raised Sunday to orange, which is "high" alert, fans were searched with a metal detector wand. Fans carrying bags continued to have those bags searched. ... To make room for Allen, the Sonics placed F Ansu Sesay on the injured list with a sprained left ring finger. ... Sonics starting PG Brent Barry missed his third straight game with a strained left hip flexor. Coach Nate McMillan said Barry thinks he might be able to play Saturday against Minnesota. ... Ridnour started at point guard for the Sonics for the second straight game because Daniels is hampered by an abdominal strain.
